        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Livius, medulla Romani ingenii, et nervus animi virilis: statim post Sallustium, ipsumq[ue] C[a]esarem, instructissimus ad 
                        conscribendam Romanam Historiam; maxime omnium seriam, atq[ue] solidam.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Livy" />
                    <person name="Sallust"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="medulla Romani ingenii"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Livy, the marrow of Roman ingenuity and the strength of the manly mind: he comes directly after Sallust and Caesar himself as the most 
                skilled for writing Roman history, sober and substantial to the highest degree of all.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Livianarum ferm&egrave; concionum, perinsignis qu[a]edam; et Imperatoria, et Senatoria Maiestas, atq[ue] dignitas. 
                        Multae sententi[a]e, utriq[ue] Militi[a]e aptae, et in suo foro exquisit[a]e. Synopsis qu[a]edam collectarum a Perionio Concionum. 
                        Digna in singulis generibus curiosa Analyse. Ut sunt plaeraq[ue] prudenter, arguteq[ue] elegantia.
                        Sed harum concionum nemo lautior censor, quam Quinctilianus, aut magnificentior pr[a]eco.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Livy" />
                    <person name="Joachim Perion" />
                    <person name="Quintilian"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Of practically [all] Livy’s speeches a very remarkable one: it has both imperial and senatorial majesty and dignity. 
                Many maxims suitable for either kind of military service, and carefully investigated in his own court of law. 
                There is a kind of summary of the speeches collected by Perionius. Worth a careful analysis in each of its categories, as most are elegant 
                in a judicious and bright way. But noone is a finer critic of these or a more distinguished announcer than Quintilian.           
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        {Ciceronis similior C[a]esar: Sallustii tij Livius: Livij Quinctilianus: Omnium Velleius. Tacitus esse maluit suus: Seneca esse voluit 
                        suissimus. Poetarum nemo delectu verboru[m], phrasium, sententiarumq[ue] affinior Ciceroni, C[a]esari, et Terentio, quam Virgilius. 
                        Ut fere non magis poeta videatur, qu&agrave;m orator, aut historicus. Tam est exquisite elegans, et prudens.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar" />
                    <person name="Cicero" />
                    <person name="Livy" />
                    <person name="Saullust" />
                    <person name="Quintilian" />
                    <person name="Marcus Velleius Paterculus" />
                    <person name="Tacitus" />
                    <person name="Seneca" />
                    <person name="Marcus Terentius Varro" />
                    <person name="Virgil" />
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Caesar is more similar to Cicero, Livy to Sallust; Quintilian to Livy, Velleius Paterculus to all. Tacitus preferred to be his own man, 
                Seneca wanted to be himself in the highest degree. Of the poets noone is more akin to Cicero, Caesar and Terentius in choice of words, 
                diction and observations than Virgil. So that he practically seems less to be a poet than an orator or historian. So meticulously elegant 
                and prudent he is.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Invectiva, s[upr]a.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Attack, [see] above.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Qui vult Livius penitus percipere, diligenter legat Pontani Actium, de historia dialogum. Nec unq[uam] obliviscatur, Quinctilianum 
                        caeteris Romanoru[m] historicis praetulisse Livium, ac Sallustium: alterumq[ue] Herodoto, alteru[m] Thucydidi composuisse, qui in 
                        dicendo fuere mirabiles. Scite Servilius Novianus: pares eos esse magis, quam similes. Sit Cicero elegantior paulo, aut concinnior: 
                        at penetrantior est Livius, saepe pressior, plaerunq[ue] nervosior, et non raro aliquid promit magis reconditum. Da saltem Ciceronis 
                        phrasin: Livii emphasin.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Livy"/>
                <person name="Giovanni Pontano"/>
                <person name="Quintilian"/>
                <person name="Sallust"/>
                <person name="Herodotos"/>
                <person name="Thucydides"/>
                    <person name="Servilius Novianus"/> <!-- LS, I added this to the Person list -->
                <person name="Cicero"/>
                <book title="Actius"/> <!-- LS, I added this to the book list -->
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Who wants to understand Livy completely, should carefully read Actius, a dialogue about history by Pontanus. And he should never forget that 
                Quintilian preferred Livy and Sallust to the other historians of the Romans, and equated the one to Herodotos and the other to Thucydides, 
                who were wonderful in making speeches. Servilius Novianus [wrote] adroitly that they are equal rather than similar. Cicero may be a bit more 
                elegant or clever, but Livy is more thorough and often more concise, and generally more powerful, and not seldom brings forth something more 
                concealed. Anyhow, give [me] Cicero’s diction and Livy’s rhetorical stress.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Tolle conciones: restabunt fragmenta: ait ille.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Remove the speeches: they will remain fragments, he says.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        {Oratori, pragmatico legato, regio consiliario, aulico deniq[ue] aut urbano politico, multi hic eximii, et conspicui Iconismi. 
                        Nullius fere emphasis, in quovis causaru[m] genere nervosior, aut efficatior.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Here for the orator, pragmatic ambassador, royal counsellor, finally the courtly or urban politician many outstanding and striking portrayals.
                Nobody’s rhetorical stress in whatever kind of subject is more powerful or effective.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
